## .NET 8 Migration: `TimedExecutor`

### Key Breaking Changes

| .NET Framework API | .NET 8 Status |
|---|---|
| `Thread.Abort()` | Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` |

### Migrated Code

```csharp
public class TimedExecutor
{
    public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);

        var task = Task.Run(() => work(), cts.Token);

        try
        {
            // Block with the same semantics as thread.Join(timeout)
            if (task.Wait(timeout))
                return task.Result; // unwraps AggregateException on faults
        }
        catch (AggregateException ex) when (ex.InnerException is not null)
        {
            // Preserve original exception behavior
            throw new AggregateException(ex.InnerException);
        }

        // Signal cancellation — the work must cooperate to stop
        cts.Cancel();
        throw new TimeoutException(
            $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
    }
}
```

### Cooperative cancellation (preferred pattern)

The original `Thread.Abort()` forcibly killed work. In .NET 8, cancellation is **cooperative** — the work must opt in:

```csharp
public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<CancellationToken, T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
{
    using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);
    var token = cts.Token;

    try
    {
        return Task.Run(() => work(token), token).GetAwaiter().GetResult();
    }
    catch (OperationCanceledException) when (token.IsCancellationRequested)
    {
        throw new TimeoutException(
            $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
    }
}
```

Callers then check the token:

```csharp
executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(ct =>
{
    foreach (var item in items)
    {
        ct.ThrowIfCancellationRequested();
        Process(item);
    }
    return result;
}, TimeSpan.FromSeconds(30));
```

### Pitfalls

1. **No forced termination** — If `work` ignores the `CancellationToken`, it keeps running after timeout. There is no .NET 8 equivalent of `Abort()`. Design work to check the token at regular intervals.

2. **`Task.Result` wraps in `AggregateException`** — Use `.GetAwaiter().GetResult()` to get the original exception unwrapped.

3. **Thread pool vs. dedicated thread** — `Task.Run` uses the thread pool. If the work is long-blocking, consider `Task.Factory.StartNew` with `TaskCreationOptions.LongRunning` to avoid starving the pool.

4. **`default(T)` race condition** — The original code had a subtle bug: if the thread was aborted, `result` could remain `default`. The task-based version avoids this since `Task.Result` is only accessible on completion.

5. **`Thread.ResetAbort()` callers** — Any downstream code catching `ThreadAbortException` must be rewritten to catch `OperationCanceledException` instead.
